div1.p: The President of the United States of America,
To the Marshal of the Western District of Washington, - Greeting:

You are hereby commanded that of the goods and chattels of H. C. Littooy in your district, you cause to be made the sum of Ten and 00/100 DOLLARS to satisfy a Judgement lately rendered in the Circuit Court of the United States, for the District of Washington, against H. C. Littooy for the damages which Edward Cudihee, Sheriff of King County, Washington. had sustained as well by reason of as forthe costs and charges in and about that suit expended, whereof the said H. C. Littooy stands convicted as appears of record.

And if sufficient goods and chattels of the said H. C. Littooy cannot be found within your district, that then you cause the amount of the said H. C. Littooy to be made of the real estate, lands and tenements whereof the said H. C. Littoy was seized on the said 20th day of July, 1904. A-D-L or at any time afterwards, is whose hands swear the name may be, and have you that money together with this writ, with your doings thereon, before the Judges of said Circuit Court, and the Court House thereof, in the City of Seattle and County of King, District of Washington, on the 10th day of July, 1905, to satisfy the Judgement so rendered as aforesaid.

Witness, the Honorable MELVILLE W. FULLER, Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States of America, this 10th day of May, in the year of our Lord One Thousand EightNine Hundred and Ninety five and of our Independence the one hundred and twenty-ninth.
Attest: my hand and the Seal of said Circuit Court the day and year last those written.
By R. M. Hopkins, Deputy Clerk.

Received this writ on the 10th day of May 1905 A.D. and executed the same by collecting the amount of the Execution $13.00 Dollars which sum I have paid to the Clerk of this court as I am above commanded.
U.S. Circuit Court, NINTH CIRCUIT, District of Western Washington.
In re application of H. C. Littooy for a writ of habeas corpus.
